<HEAD>BLUE-BEARD; OR, FEMALE CURIOSITY!</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT I.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE I.</HI> A Turki&s;h Village&mdash;A Romantick, Mountainous Coun|try beyond it.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SELIM <HI>is di&s;covered under</HI> FATIMA's <HI>Window, to which a Ladder of Silken Ropes is fa&s;tened</HI>. DAWN.</STAGE>
<STAGE>DUET&mdash;SELIM AND FATIMA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SELIM.</SPEAKER>
<L>TWILIGHT glimmers o'er the Steep:</L>
<L>Fatima! Fatima! wake&s;t thou, dear?</L>
<L>Grey-eyed Morn begins to peep:</L>
<L>Fatima! Fatima! Selim's here!</L>
<L>Here are true-love's cords attaching</L>
<L>To your window.&mdash;Li&s;t! Li&s;t!</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Fatima opens the Window.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Deare&s;t Selim! I've been watching;</L>
<GAP DESC="MISSING" EXTENT="1 page">
<L><PB N="2" REF="8">Yes, I &s;ee the &s;ilken twi&s;t.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Down, Down, Down, Down, Down!</L>
<L>Down the Ladder gently trip;</L>
<L>Pit a pat, pit a pat,&mdash;ha&s;te thee, dear!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>O! I'm &s;ure my foot will &s;lip!</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>With one foot out of the Window.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Fatima!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well Selim?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Do not fear!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>She gets upon the Ladder&mdash;they keep time in &s;inging to her &s;teps as &s;he de&s;cends, towards the end of the left line &s;he reaches the ground and they embrace.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>B$$$.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Pit a pat, pit a pat, Pit a pat,</L>
<L>Pit a pat, pit a pat&mdash;Pat, Pat, Pat.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>As they embrace, Ibrahim puts his head out, from the door of the Hou&s;e.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, I raitre&s;s!&mdash;Have I caught you! <STAGE><HI>comes forward</HI></STAGE> Attempt to run away with a Man?&mdash;and, not only with a man, but a Trooper!&mdash;One of the Spahis. &mdash;Wicked Fatima!&mdash;Much as Mahomet's brood mu&s;t have increa&s;ed, there isn't one turtle in all our Prophet's pigeon-hou&s;e, that would'nt be ready to pick at you. In,&mdash;in, and repent!<STAGE><HI>pu&s;hes her into the hou&s;e.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hear me Ibrahim!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I won't hear you, as I'm a Mu&s;&s;ulman!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Credit me to &s;uppo&s;e that&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I won't credit any thing, as I'm a True Believer!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Did not you promi&s;e her to me in marriage?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Um?&mdash;Why, I did &s;ay &s;omething like getting $ $icence from the Cadi.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And, what has made you break your word?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A better Bridegroom for my daughter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why better than I?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="3" REF="9">
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He's richer.&mdash;You have your merits&mdash;but he's a Ba&s;haw, with Three Tails.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Does that make him more de&s;erving?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure it does, all the world over. Throw Riches and Power into the &s;cale, and &s;imple Merit &s;oon kicks the beam.&mdash;Now to cut the matter &s;hort. You're a very pretty Trooper; &s;o troop off: &mdash;for Abomelique&mdash;the great Abomelique, comes, this day, to carry my daughter to his magnificent Ca&s;tle, and e&s;pou&s;e her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Abomelique!&mdash;The pe&s;t of all the neigh|bouring country.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes&mdash;he's by far the be&s;t of all the neigh|bouring country.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Who deals, as all around declare, in &s;pells and magick.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye&mdash;You can't &s;ay of him, as they do of many great folks, that he's no Conjuror.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And you think this man calculated to make a good hu&s;band to Fatima?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Po&s;itively.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Better than I?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Um&mdash;Comparatively.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And you now look upon me with contempt?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Superlatively&mdash;I do, by the Temple of Mecca!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Now, by my injuries old man!&mdash;but I curb my ju&s;t re&s;entment:&mdash;You are the Father of my Fatima;&mdash;but for my Rival&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He is able enough to maintain his own cau&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="4" REF="10">
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! he &s;hall rue the day when, &s;erpent-like he &s;tung me. Yes, Abomelique!&mdash;Spite of thy wealth and power,&mdash;thy, my&s;tick &s;pells, and helli&s;h incantations,&mdash;a Soldiers vengeance &s;hall per&s;ue thee.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>QUARTETTO.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Selim.&mdash;Ibrahim.&mdash;Fatima</HI> and <HI>Irene</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Ruthle&s;s Tyrant! dread my force!</L>
<L>A Soldier's Sabre hangs o'er thee!</L>
<L>Thou &s;oon &s;halt fall a headle&s;s cor&s;e,</L>
<L>Who now would'&s;t tear my love from me.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>How prettily, now, he rails!</L>
<L>But tisn't &s;o ea&s;ily done as &s;aid</L>
<L>To &s;mite a Ba&s;haw, and cut off the Head</L>
<L>Of a Man who has got three Tails.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Fatima and Irene come from the Hou&s;e, and kneel to Ibrahim.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI> &amp; <HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Turn, turn, my Father! turn thee hither!</L>
<L>A Daughter would thy pity move!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why doom the opening Ro&s;e to wither?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Both.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why blight the early bud of Love?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>O! how teizing!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>O! how trying! O! how vexing</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Are the fears which
<LIST>
<ITEM>Fathers prove</ITEM>
<ITEM>Lovers prove</ITEM>
<ITEM>Daughters prove</ITEM>
</LIST></L>
<L>How di&s;tre&s;&s;ing! How perplexing</L>
<L>Are the cares that wait on Love!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI> &amp; <HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hear me! Hear me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I'll not hear thee!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI> &amp; <HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Can you now our &s;uit refu&s;e?</L>
<L>Cheer me! You alone can cheer mer&mdash;</L>
<L>'Tis a wretched daughter &s;ues.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis a &s;illy daughter &s;ues.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>All.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>O! how trying! Oh! how vexing! &amp;c.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="5" REF="11">
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Dear! how can you think of marrying my Si&s;ter to this Ba&s;haw?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And pray, good mi&s;tre&s;s Irene, with all the &s;ubmi&s;&s;ion of a dutiful Father, may I crave to know your objections?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why in the fir&s;t place, then, Father, he has a Blue Beard.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And who, in the name of all the Devils, made you a judge of Beards?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I do think it was &s;ent as a puni&s;hment to him, on account of all his unfortunate wives.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! now, under favour, I do think that a man's wives are puni&s;hment enough, in them&s;elves. Prai&s;ed be the whole&s;ome Law of Mahomet that &s;tinted a Turk to only four at a time!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The Ba&s;haw had never more than one at a time;&mdash;and 'tis whi&s;pered that he beheaded the poor &s;ouls one after another:&mdash;for in &s;pite of his power there's no preventing talking.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That's true, indeed;&mdash;and, if cutting off women's heads won't prevent talking, I know of no method likely to pro&s;per!&mdash;But, I'll make You &s;i|lent, Mi&s;tre&s;s, depend on't.&mdash;No more of this prate!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I have done, Father!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Prepare to take up your abode with your Si&s;ter, at the Ca&s;tle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>O, I am very, very glad I am to be with her! Are not you, Fatima?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I am indeed, Irene. A loved Si&s;ter's pre|&s;ence will be a con&s;olation to me, in my mi&s;eries.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="6" REF="12">
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Perhaps I may contrive to go with you, too.&mdash;If I could bring it about, I &s;hould dwell there in all the re&s;pect due to a relation of the mighty Abomelique. Let me once get footing in Old Three-Tails Ca&s;tle, and I'll tickle up the Slaves for a great man's Father-in-Law, I'll warrant me!&mdash; Hark!&mdash;I hear him on the march over the mount|ain:&mdash;and here are all our neighbours, pouring out of their hou&s;es, to &s;ee the proce&s;&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>The Sun ri&s;es gradually.&mdash;A March is heard at a great di&s;tance.</HI>&mdash;ABOMELIQUE, <HI>and a magnificent train, ap|pear, at the top of the Mountain &mdash;They de&s;cend through a winding path:&mdash;Sometimes they are lo&s;t to the &s;ight, to mark the irregularities of the road. The Mu&s;ick grows &s;tronger as they approach.&mdash;At length</HI>, ABO|MELIQUE's <HI>train range them&s;elves on each &s;ide of the Stage, and &s;ing the Chorus, as he marches down through their ranks.&mdash;The Villagers come from their Hou&s;es</HI>.</STAGE>
<Q><TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1>
<HEAD>GRAND CHORUS.</HEAD>
<L>Mark his approach with Thunder! Strike on the trembling Spheres!</L>
<L>With martial cra&s;h,</L>
<L>The Cymbals cla&s;h;</L>
<L>'Tis the Ba&s;haw appears.</L>
<L>War in his eye-ball gli&s;tens! Slave of his lip is Law;</L>
<L>Our Life, and Death</L>
<L>Hang on his breath:&mdash;</L>
<L>Hail to the great Ba&s;haw!</L>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<SP>
<PB N="7" REF="13">
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Now, Ibrahim;&mdash;I come to claim my Bride,&mdash;the lovely Fatima. To take this village ro&s;e from the ob&s;cure and lowly &s;hade, and place her in a warmer &s;oil; where the full Sun of Wealth &s;hall &s;hine upon her, and add a richer glow to the &s;weet blu&s;h of beauty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mo&s;t pui&s;&s;ant Ba&s;haw!&mdash;I am proud that any twig of mine is thought worthy of a place in your Shrubbery.&mdash;Irene, as you de&s;ired, &s;hall go with Fa|tima, as companion. For my&s;elf, mighty Sir, I am a tough Stick, &s;omewhat dry, and a little too old, perhaps, to be moved:&mdash;but, to &s;ay the truth, &s;ince you are going to take off my &s;uckers, if I were to be tran&s;planted along with them, I think I &s;hould thrive.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>It &s;hall be order'd &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Shall it!&mdash;Then, if I don't make &s;hift to flouri&s;h, cut me down, and make fire-wood of me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Be &s;atisfied&mdash;you &s;hall along with us There &s;hall not be one countenance on which my power, and this day's fe&s;tival, does not impre&s;s a &s;mile.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That's fal&s;e, by Mahomet!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How now!&mdash;Who dares utter that?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h!&mdash;<STAGE><HI>Stopping Selims mouth.</HI></STAGE> He's no|body&mdash;Only a poor mad Trooper.&mdash;You may know he's a Trooper by his &s;wearing.&mdash;Beneath your mighty notice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What prompts him to this boldne&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Injury&mdash;You have ba&s;ely wronged me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="8" REF="14">
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ra&s;h fool!&mdash;know my power and re&s;pect it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>When Power is re&s;pected, it's ba&s;is mu&s;t be Ju&s;tice. 'Tis then an edifice that gives the hum|ble &s;helter and they reverence it:&mdash;But, 'tis a hated &s;hallow fabrick, that rears it&s;elf upon oppre&s;&s;ion:&mdash; the breath of the di&s;contented &s;wells into a gale around it, 'till it totters.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Speak&mdash;how are you aggrieved?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Let me inform him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>O, plague!&mdash;Hold your tongue!&mdash;A wo|man always makes bad wor&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Proceed, &s;weet Fatima!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I was poor, and happy;&mdash;for my wi&s;hes were lowly as my &s;tate.&mdash;Content and Peace dwelt in our Cottage;&mdash;nor were the&s;e &s;miling inmates ruffled, when Love &s;tole in, and found a &s;helter in my bo&s;om. My Father placed my hand in this young Soldier's, and taught me that our fortunes &s;oon &s;hould be united.&mdash;Poor Selim's &s;oul &s;poke in his eyes, and mine replied, (for true love's eyes are eloquent) that, through my life, I wi&s;hed no other protector than a brave youth, who&s;e lot, being hum|ble like my own, the more endeared him to me. Our hopes and joys were ripening daily: You came, and all are blighted!<STAGE><HI>falls in Selim's arms.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Tear them a&s;under.&mdash;In&s;ulted! and by a Slave that&mdash;
<STAGE>SELIM <HI>offers to draw, and is re&s;trained by</HI> ABOMELIQUE's <HI>Attendants</HI>.</STAGE>
<PB N="9" REF="15">
Thou art beneath my notice.&mdash;You, Fatima, mu&s;t to the Ca&s;tle.&mdash;Prepare the Palanquin! <STAGE><HI>to the At|tendants</HI></STAGE> We are advanced too far, Lady&mdash;we can|not now recede.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>A Magnificent Palanquin is brought in, drawn by Black Slaves.</HI></STAGE>
<Q><TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1>
<HEAD>GRAND CHORUS.</HEAD>
<L>Advance!</L>
<L>See us the Bride attending!</L>
<L>Echo &s;hall now the chaunt prolong,</L>
<L>Torn with a lu&s;ty Turki&s;h Song,</L>
<L>While the Star of the World is a&s;cending.</L>
<STAGE>ABOMELIQUE <HI>leads</HI> FATIMA <HI>towards the Palanquin</HI>.</STAGE>
<L>Hark to the Drum!</L>
<L>Come, Comrades, Come!</L>
<L>Time will not brook delaying.&mdash;</L>
<STAGE>ABOMELIQUE <HI>forces</HI> FATIMA <HI>into the Palanquin, who &s;truggles</HI>.</STAGE>
<L>See &s;he re&s;i&s;ts&mdash;her Struggles note!</L>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI> &amp; <HI>Fat.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>O give me
<LIST>
<ITEM>her</ITEM>
<ITEM>him</ITEM>
</LIST>
on whom I dote!</L>
<STAGE>ABOMELIQUE <HI>draws his &s;abre&mdash;all the</HI> SLAVES <HI>draw</HI>.</STAGE>
<L>Sabres are gleaming round the throat</L>
<L>Of Beauty di&s;obeying.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt, hurrying off</HI> FATIMA. IRENE <HI>is &s;eated with her in the Palanquin&punc;</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE II.</HI> A Hall in Abomelique's Ca&s;tle.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> BEDA, (<HI>with a Guittar.</HI>)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Where can he be loitering &s;o long!&mdash;Why, Shacabac!&mdash;Poor melancholy fool! he's in &s;ome dark corner of the Ca&s;tle, now,&mdash;moping, and &s;ighing as
<PB N="10" REF="16">
u&s;ual&mdash;This is the hour he &s;hould come to take his daily le&s;&s;on with me on the Guittar. Mu&s;ick is the only thing that makes him merry.&mdash;Why, Shaca|bac!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SHACABAC, (<HI>with a Guittar.</HI>)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Here I am, Beda!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why, where have you been, all this time, Shacabac?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Getting all in readine&s;s for the Ba&s;haw's re|turn, with his intended Bride.&mdash;They &s;ay &s;he's very hand&s;ome.&mdash;Poor &s;oul!&mdash;I pity her.<STAGE><HI>half a&s;ide</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Pity a woman becau&s;e &s;he is hand&s;ome!&mdash; Pray, then, keep out of my way, for I don't like to be pitied.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Did I &s;ay, Pity?&mdash;Oh no&mdash;I didn't intend that&mdash;Heigho!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Now what can you be &s;ighing for?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That wasn't &s;ighing.&mdash;I'm like our old blind camel,&mdash;a little &s;hort winded, that's all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I'm &s;ure, Shacabac, you ought to be the happie&s;t creature in the Ca&s;tle.&mdash;The Ba&s;haw loads you with his favours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>O, very heavily, indeed!&mdash;I don't di&s;pute that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You are his chief attendant; and he honours you with more employment than all the other &s;laves put together.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="11" REF="17">
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Works me like a mule;&mdash;it would be un|grateful to deny it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And every body thinks that he tru&s;ts you with all his &s;ecrets.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>Alarmed</HI></STAGE>No!&mdash;Do they think that?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; and, to &s;ay truth, you keep them lock'd up as clo&s;e&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>&s;tarting</HI></STAGE>Lock'd up!&mdash;how!&mdash;why, you&mdash; where &s;hould I keep them lock'd up?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>In your brea&s;t, to be &s;ure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh!&mdash;Yes&mdash;yes:&mdash;That is if he tru&s;ts me with any:&mdash;but to think that a Ba&s;haw would tell his &s;ecrets to a &s;lave!&mdash;non&s;en&s;e!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, it isn't for nothing he takes you to talk with him, in private, in the Blue Chamber.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>very earne&s;tly</HI></STAGE>Don't mention that, Be|da!&mdash;Never mention the Blue Chamber again!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why, what harm is there in the Blue Chamber?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>None in the world:&mdash;but you know I'm full of melancholy fancies:&mdash;and I never go into that Blue Chamber that I don't feel as if I were tor|mented with Devils.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mercy!&mdash;What Devils, Shacabac?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>recovering him&s;elf, &amp; &s;miling</HI></STAGE>Only Blue Devils, Beda!&mdash;Nothing more. Come&mdash;Hang Sorrow!&mdash; Let's &s;trike up a tune, on the Guittar.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, that makes you merry, at the wor&s;t of times.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="12" REF="18">
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That it does, Beda.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>DUET.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Shacahac</HI> and <HI>Beda</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BEDA.</SPEAKER>
<L>Yes, Beda,&mdash;This, Beda, when I melancholy grow,</L>
<L>This tinking heart-&s;inking &s;oon can drive away.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BEDA.</SPEAKER>
<L>When hearing &s;ounds cheering, then we blythe and jolly grow;</L>
<L>How do you, while to you, Shacabac, I play?</L>
<L>Tink, tinka, tinka, tink&mdash;the &s;weet Guittar &s;hall cheer you.</L>
<L>Clink, clinka, clinka, clink&mdash;So gaily let us &s;ing!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHAC.</SPEAKER>
<L>Tink, tinka, tinka, tink&mdash;A plea&s;ure 'tis to hear you,</L>
<L>While, neatly, you &s;weetly, &s;weetly touch the &s;tring!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BOTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tink, tinka, &amp;c.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHAC.</SPEAKER>
<L>Once &s;ighing, &s;ick, dying, Sorrow hanging over me,</L>
<L>Faint, weary, &s;ad, dreary, on the ground I lay;</L>
<L>There moaning, deep groaning, Beda did di&s;cover me&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BEDA.</SPEAKER>
<L>Strains &s;oothing, Care &s;moothing, I began to play.</L>
<L>Tink, tinka, tinka, tink,&mdash;the &s;weet Guittar could cheer you:</L>
<L>Clink, clinka, clinka, clink, &s;o gaily did I &s;ing!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SHAC.</SPEAKER>
<L>Tink, tinka, tinka, tink,&mdash;A plea&s;ure 'twas to hear you,</L>
<L>While, neatly, You &s;weetly, &s;weetly touch'd the &s;tring!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BOTH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tink, tinka, &amp;c.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="13" REF="19"><HI>A Horn is &s;ounded without.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hark!&mdash;the Horn &s;ounds at the Ca&s;tle Gate.&mdash;The Ba&s;haw is return'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And brings his Bride with him. I long to &s;ee her! I mu&s;t join the re&s;t of the &s;laves pre&s;ently. You know, Shacabac, we are all to kneel, and cry "May &s;he live long and happy!"</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Heaven &s;end &s;he may!&mdash;Hu&s;h! The Ba|&s;haw!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ABOMELIQUE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, you are here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To obey your plea&s;ure. Your Slave hum|bly tru&s;ts that, in preparing for our new Mi&s;tre&s;s, nothing has been neglected.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I commend your care;&mdash;and, while the lovely Fatima is in&s;pecting her apartments, I have employ|ment for you. You mu&s;t attend me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Whither, mighty Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To the Blue Chamber.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The Blue Cha&mdash;<STAGE><HI>drops the Guittar</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What ails the driveller?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;Nothing&mdash;nothing.&mdash;That terrible &s;ound &s;ets me a &s;hivering!<STAGE><HI>half a&s;ide.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What &s;ay you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ay the Guittar fell to the ground, and I was afraid of it's &s;hivering.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Attend me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="14" REF="20">
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I follow.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit Abomelique, followed by Shacabac.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Poor Shacabac! what can be the matter with him!&mdash;Perhaps he has been cro&s;&s;ed in Love&mdash; and, now I think of it, he mu&s;t have a mi&s;tre&s;s &s;ome where&mdash;or he never would be &s;o often alone with me without &s;aying one tender thing to me&mdash;Ah, Love, Love!&mdash;I never &s;hall forget my poor, dear, lo&s;t Ca&s;&s;ib.</P>
</SP>
<DIV4 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG.</HEAD>
<LG>
<L>His &s;parkling eyes were dark as jet;</L>
<L>Chica, Chica, Chica, Cho.</L>
<L>Can I my comely Turk forget?&mdash;</L>
<L>Oh! never, never, never, no!</L>
<L>Did he not watch 'till Night did fall,</L>
<L>And &s;ail in &s;ilence on the Sea;</L>
<L>Did he not climb our &s;ea-girt wall,</L>
<L>To talk &s;o lovingly to me?&mdash;</L>
<L>O! his &s;parkling eyes, &amp;c.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>His Lips were of the coral hue,</L>
<L>His Teeth of ivory &s;o white;</L>
<L>But he was hurried from my view,</L>
<L>Who gave to me &s;o much delight!</L>
<L>And, why &s;hould tender Lovers part!</L>
<L>And why &s;hould Fathers cruel be!</L>
<L>Why bid me bani&s;h from my heart</L>
<L>A heart &s;o full of Love for me!</L>
<L>O! his &s;parkling eyes, &amp;c<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="15" REF="21">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE III.</HI> A Blue Apartment<NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot">The Dialogue of this Scene has undergone &s;ome alteration, &s;ince it was fir&s;t repre&s;ented: by which means the Blue Apart|ment is not &s;hewn 'till the Second Act. The Author, however, prefers printing it as it was originally written.</NOTE></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>A winding Stair-ca&s;e on one &s;ide.&mdash;A Large door in the middle of the Flat.&mdash;Over the door, a Picture of Abomelique, kneeling in amorous &s;upplication to a beautiful woman.&mdash;Other Pictures, and Devices, on Subjects of Love, decorate the Apartment.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE>ABOMELIQUE <HI>and</HI> SHACABAC <HI>de&s;cend the Stair</HI>.</STAGE>
<STAGE>SHACABAC <HI>in apparent terror</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You know my purpo&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I gue&s;s it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why do you tremble?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The air of this Apartment chills me:&mdash; and the bu&s;ine&s;s we are going upon isn't the be&s;t to in&s;pire courage.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Fool!&mdash;When this my&s;terious Portal &s;hall be open'd, what ha&s;t thou to dread?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, nothing at all. The inhabitants of the inner apartment might terrify a man of tender nerves;&mdash;but what are they to me?&mdash;Only a few fly|ing Phantoms, &s;heeted Spectres, &s;kipping Skeletons, and grinning Gho&s;ts at their gambols:&mdash;and as to tho&s;e who had once the honour to be your wives,&mdash; poor &s;ouls!&mdash;they are harmle&s;s enough, now, what|ever they might have been formerly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Twas to prevent the harm with which
<PB N="16" REF="22">
their conduct threaten'd me, that they have &s;uffer'd. Their crimes were on their heads.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then their Crimes were as cleanly taken off their &s;houlders as Scymetar could carry them.&mdash; That Curio&s;ity &s;hould co&s;t &s;o much!&mdash;If all women were to forfeit their heads for being inqui&s;itive, what a number of &s;weet, pretty, female faces we &s;hould lo&s;e in the world!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Such puni&s;hment might outrun even Tur|ki&s;h Ju&s;tice&mdash;but in me, 'tis prudence; Self pre|&s;ervation.&mdash;You are not ignorant of the prediction.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That it is your fate to marry, and your Life will be endangered by the Curio&s;ity of the woman whom you e&s;pou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Thou ha&s;t the &s;ecret. Dare not to breathe it, or&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Don't look &s;o terrible then,&mdash;for, if you &s;care away my &s;en&s;es, who knows but the &s;ecret may pop out along with them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I know thou dare&s;t not utter it. The my&s;tick ceremonies, in which, from mere nece&s;&s;ity, I have employ'd thee&mdash;thou weak and unapt agent&mdash; bear in them a &s;upernatural force, fettering thy ton|gue in &s;il$nce. <STAGE><HI>gives him a Key decorated with Jewels</HI></STAGE> Take the Key: apply it to the door.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I&mdash;but I was always from a b$y, the mere&s;t bungler at a Lock that&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Da&s;tard!&mdash;Thou know'&s;t how readily 'twill open.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But mu&s;t I once more open it to&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="17" REF="23">
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Be &s;peedy! This Tali&s;man mu&s;t, ere my marriage rites are &s;olemnized, be placed within the Tomb of tho&s;e who&s;e ra&s;hne&s;s has laid them cold beneath the icy hand of Death.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mercy on us!&mdash;I know not for the icy hand of Death:&mdash;But if Fear would do me the favour to keep his chilly paws off me, I &s;hould be much war|mer than I am at pre&s;ent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No dallying.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I obey.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>SHACABAC <HI>puts the Key into the Lock; the Door in|&s;tantly &s;inks, with a tremendous cra&s;h: and the</HI> Blue Chamber <HI>appears &s;treaked with vivid &s;treams of Blood. The figures in the Picture, over the door, change their po&s;ition, and</HI> ABOMELIQUE <HI>is repre&s;ented in the action of beheading the Beauty he was, before, &s;upplicating.&mdash;The Pictures, and Devices, of Love, change to &s;ubjects of Horror and Death. The</HI> inte|rior apartment <HI>(which the &s;inking of the door di&s;co|vers,) exhibits various Tombs, in a &s;epulchral build|ing;&mdash;in the mid&s;t of which gha&s;tly and &s;upernatural forms are &s;een;&mdash;&s;ome in motion, &s;ome fix'd&mdash;In the centre, is a large Skeleton &s;eated on a tomb, (with a Dart in his hand) and, over his head, in characters of Blood, is written</HI>
<Q>"THE PUNISHMENT OF CURIOSITY."</Q></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Thou &s;ee&s;t yon fle&s;hle&s;s form.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>pointing to the Skeleton.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>O, yes!&mdash;and my own fle&s;h crawls when|ever I look upon him.<STAGE><HI>giving Abomelique the Key.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="18" REF="24">
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Henceforward he mu&s;t be my de&s;tiny. Dae|mon of Blood!&mdash;<STAGE>addre&s;&s;ing the Skeleton</STAGE> Death's Courier!&mdash;who&s;e &s;port it it to &s;ound War's Clari|on;&mdash;to whet$ the knife of Suicide!&mdash;to lead the hired Murderer to the Sleeping Babe; and, with a gha&s;tly &s;mile of triumph, to regi&s;ter the Slaughter'd, who prematurely drop in Nature's Charnel-hou&s;e;&mdash; here, here have I pent thee!&mdash;A pri&s;oner to my Art,&mdash;here&mdash;to circum&s;cribe thy general purpo&s;es, for my particular good&mdash;twelve winters have I kept thee!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Have you!&mdash;Allah pre&s;erve us!&mdash;but I mu&s;t &s;ay that, con&s;idering the time, he looks &s;o lean that he does his keeper no credit.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Approach him with re&s;pect.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Who, I?&mdash;I'd rather keep at a re&s;pectful di&s;tance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Take this Tali&s;man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis a Dagger.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis a charmed one. While it remains beneath the foot of that &s;ame gha&s;tly form, I am free from mortal power. Another hand than mine mu&s;t place it there. Thou mu&s;t perform the office.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Gives him the Talisman.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mu&s;t I!&mdash;well&mdash;I&mdash;<STAGE><HI>approaching the figure</HI></STAGE> O, Mahome$!&mdash;If ever I get away &s;afe from this gentleman who has jumped out of his Skin, I &s;hall jump out of my own, for joy!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="19" REF="25">SHACABAC <HI>lays the Dagger at the foot of the Skele|ton.&mdash;It Thunders and Lightens violently. The in|&s;cription, over the Skeleton's head, changes to the fol|lowing</HI>&mdash;
<Q>"THIS SEPULCHRE SHALL INCLOSE HER WHO MAY ENDANGER THE LIFE OF ABOMELI|QUE"&mdash;</Q>
<HI>The Skeleton rai&s;es his arm which holds the Dart; then lets his arm fall again.</HI> SHACABAC <HI>&s;taggers from the Sepulchre, into the Blue Chamber, and falls on his face; when the Door, in&s;tantly ri&s;ing, clo&s;es the in|terior building.&mdash;The &s;treaks of blood vani&s;h from the walls of the Blue Chamber, and</HI> ABOMELIQUE's <HI>Pic|ture, with the other Pictures, and Devices, re&s;ume their original appearance</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>It omens pro&s;perou&s;ly! This Sepulchre &s;hall inclo&s;e Her who may endanger the Life of Abome|lique.&mdash;Her death then is the penalty of her ra&s;hne&s;s. May Fatima be prudent, and avoid it.&mdash;Rou&s;e thee, dull fool!&mdash;Thy Ta&s;k is ended: ari&s;e, and follow me hence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That I will, if my Legs have power to carry me.<STAGE><HI>getting up</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hark!&mdash;I hear a foot in yonder gallery:&mdash; A&s;cend the Stairs with me, in &s;ilence. Chattering will co&s;t thy Life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then I am &s;ure you mu&s;t pull out my teeth,
<PB N="20" REF="26">
for they chatter in &s;pite of me. <STAGE><HI>Abomelique makes a &s;ign to him to follow</HI></STAGE> I attend!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>They a&s;cend the Stair-ca&s;e, and the Scene clo&s;es.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE, IV.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>An Apartment in the Ca&s;tle.&mdash;Enter</HI> FATIMA <HI>and</HI> IRENE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Prythee, deare&s;t &s;i&s;ter, take comfort.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Where &s;hall I find it? Torn from the man I love, and forced into the arms of one whom I, and all around, dete&s;t, where &s;hould I look for comfort! My waking thoughts are torments; and, &s;ince this marriage was propo&s;ed, my very dreams have fore|boded mi&s;ery.</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Fatima.</HI></STAGE>
<LG>
<L>While, pen&s;ive, I thought on my Love,</L>
<L>The Moon, on the Mountain, was bright;</L>
<L>And Philomel, down in the grove,</L>
<L>Broke, &s;weetly, the &s;ilence of Night.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>O, I wi&s;h'd that the tear-drop would flow!</L>
<L>But I felt too much angui&s;h to weep;</L>
<L>'Till, worn with the weight of my woe,</L>
<L>I &s;unk on my pillow, to &s;leep.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Methought that my Love, as I lay,</L>
<L>His ringlets all clotted with gore,</L>
<L>In the palene&s;s of Death, &s;eem'd to &s;ay,</L>
<L>"Alas! we mu&s;t never meet more!"</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>"Yes, yes, my beloved! we mu&s;t part;"</L>
<L>"The Steel of my Rival was true;&mdash;</L>
<L>"The A&s;&s;a&s;&s;in has &s;truck on that heart,"</L>
<L>"Which beat with &s;uch fervour for you."</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<SP>
<PB N="21" REF="27">
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why, to be &s;ure, 'tis a &s;ad thing to lo&s;e Se|lim.&mdash;He is a good youth.&mdash;And we women have, &s;omehow, &s;uch a plea&s;ure in looking at a good young man, when he happens to be very hand&s;ome! Yet the Ba&s;haw, bating his Beard, i&s;n't &s;o very ugly neither. Then, you know, he rolls in riches.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He abu&s;es them, Irene. Wealth, when it's purpo&s;e is perverted, makes the po&s;&s;e&s;&s;or odious. When virtuous men have gold they purcha&s;e their own happine&s;s, by making others happy:&mdash;Heap trea&s;ure on the vicious, they &s;trengthen their inju&s;tice with the &s;weet means of Charity, and turn the poor man's ble&s;&s;ing to a cur&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well now it's a great pity you happen'd to love Selim fir&s;t. Who knows but the Ba&s;haw may turn out good to us, after all. See what fine cloaths he has given us already.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Alas, my &s;i&s;ter! the&s;e gay trappings com|municate no plea&s;ure to an aching heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h they could &s;ee us in them, in our village, for all that. Then we are to have a fine fea&s;t, to|night, in honour of your nuptials, which are to take place to-morrow.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SHACABAC.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, the Ba&s;haw waits, to attend you, to the illuminated Garden.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There&mdash;the illuminated Garden! I told you &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<GAP DESC="MISSING" EXTENT="1 page">
<SP>
<PB N="22" REF="28">
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I attend him. Come, Si&s;ter.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt Fatima and Irene.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Poor &s;oul! mu&s;t &s;he be &s;acrificed, too, to the Ba&s;haw's cruelty! His &s;avage &s;pirit &s;ettles all family di&s;putes with the edge of the Scymetar.</P>
</SP>
<DIV4 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG.</HEAD>
<LG>
<L>A Fond Hu&s;band, will, after a conjugal Strife,</L>
<L>Ki&s;s, forgive, weep, and fall on the neck of his Wife.</L>
<L>But Abomelique's wife other conduct may dread&mdash;</L>
<L>When he falls on her Neck, 'tis to cut off her head.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>How many there are, when a Wife plays the fool,</L>
<L>Will argue the point with her, calmly, and cool;</L>
<L>The Ba&s;haw, who don't reli&s;h debates of this &s;ort,</L>
<L>Cuts the Woman, as well as the Argument, &s;hort.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>But, whatever her errors, 'tis mighty unfair</L>
<L>To cut off her Head, ju&s;t as if 'twere all Hair;&mdash;</L>
<L>For, this truth is maintain'd by Philo&s;ophers &s;till,&mdash;</L>
<L>That the Hair grows again, but the Head never will.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>And, among all the ba&s;e&s;t, &s;ure he is mo&s;t ba&s;e,</L>
<L>Who can view, then demoli&s;h, a Woman's &s;weet face!</L>
<L>Her &s;miles might the malice of Devils di&s;arm;</L>
<L>And the Devil take Him who would offer her harm!</L>
</LG>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV4>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="5" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="23" REF="29">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE V.</HI> A Garden&mdash;brilliantly and fancifully illuminated&mdash;A Fountain playing in the middle of it&mdash;An elevated Sofa on one &s;ide, under a rich Canopy.</HEAD>
<STAGE>A LARGE COMPANY OF SLAVES <HI>di&s;covered&mdash;&s;ome</HI> DAN|CEARS&mdash;<HI>others with Mu&s;ical in&s;truments&mdash;They all ap|pear as preparing for an entertainment</HI>.</STAGE>
<STAGE>BEDA <HI>is foremo&s;t among them</HI>.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> IBRAHIM.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That's right! You poor abominable Devils, who have the happine&s;s to be Slaves to my Son-in-law, that's right! Thrum you guittars, puff your trumpets, and blow your flutes, in honour of your new Mi&s;tre&s;s, my daughter. Come here you long winded dog!&mdash;<STAGE><HI>to a &s;lave with a trumpet</HI></STAGE> Tell me who I am.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Slave.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You are old Ibrahim.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Old Ibrahim!&mdash;The&s;e Slaves are remarka|bly free!&mdash;I am the Father of the Lady who is to be Wife of the Man, who is the Ma&s;ter of you.&mdash; What a fine thing it is to be Father-in-law to Three Tails!&mdash;<STAGE><HI>Sees Beda</HI></STAGE> O, dear! there's a pretty black-eyed girl!&mdash;Come here, and tell me your name.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My name is Beda, &s;o plea&s;e you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Beda, is it?&mdash;Why you little Devil, you're an Angel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh no, Sir,&mdash;I'm only one of the family.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then give me a family ki&s;s.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="24" REF="30">
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Dear! if the Ba&s;haw &s;hould &s;ee you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then he'd &s;ay you have a good ta&s;te.&mdash; Cheer up, little one!&mdash;I rule the roa&s;t here.&mdash;It &s;han't go wor&s;e with you that I have power, and you have charms. It's amazing, when Beauty pleads with a Great Man, how much quicker it ri&s;es to promotion than ugly-faced merit.&mdash;<STAGE><HI>A Flouri&s;h of Mu&s;ick without</HI></STAGE> Silence! Here comes the great Abomelique!&mdash;Son-in-Law to me, who am the Father to the Lady, who is to marry the man, that is ma&s;ter to you.&mdash;Stand a&s;ide!&mdash;be ready&mdash;Strain your throats, kick your heels, and &s;hew obedience.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>ABOMELIQUE <HI>enters with</HI> FATIMA, IRENE <HI>accompa|nying them</HI>. ABOMELIQUE <HI>and</HI> FATIMA <HI>&s;eat them|&s;elves under the Canopy</HI>.</STAGE>
<DIV4>
<HEAD>A GRAND DANCE.</HEAD>
<STAGE>CHORUS.</STAGE>
<L>Lowly we bend in Duty.</L>
<L>Queen of the peaceful Bowers!</L>
<L>We bow to the foot-&s;teps of beauty:</L>
<L>And &s;trew her path with flowers.</L>
<L>The mellow flute is blowing,</L>
<L>Bounce goes the Tambourin;</L>
<L>Sweet harmony is flowing,</L>
<L>To welcome Beauty's Queen.</L>
</DIV4>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>END OF THE FIRST ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="act">
<PB N="25" REF="31">
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE I. A WOOD.</HEAD>
<STAGE>A COMPANY OF SPAHIS <HI>(or Turki&s;h Soldiers) di&s;|coverd in ambu&s;h</HI>. GLEE.</STAGE>
<LG>
<L>STAND clo&s;e!&mdash;Our Comrade is not come:</L>
<L>Ere this, he mu&s;t be hovering near;&mdash;</L>
<L>Give him a Signal we are here,</L>
<L>By gently tapping on the Drum.</L>
<L>Rub, Dub, Dub.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>A Comrade's wrong'd: Revenge &s;hall work:</L>
<L>Thus, till our project's ripe, we lurk;&mdash;</L>
<L>And &s;till, to mark that we are here,</L>
<L>Yet not alarm the di&s;tant ear,</L>
<L>With caution, ever and anon,</L>
<L>The Drum we gently tap upon.</L>
<L>Rub, Dub, Dub.</L>
</LG>
<SP>
<PB N="26" REF="32">
<SPEAKER>1&s;t. <HI>Spa.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Selim tarries long.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d <HI>Spa.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Di&s;appointed Love is a heavy luggage; &mdash;and he who travels with it generally proceeds &s;lowly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>3d <HI>Spa.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not when the hope of redre&s;s is pack'd up with his di&s;appointments: and Revenge has long &s;purs to quicken a dull motion.&mdash;Were you ever in love, Comrade?<STAGE><HI>to a &s;ullen rough look|ing companion.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>4th <HI>Spa.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>very gruffly</HI></STAGE>I once knew the tender pa&s;&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>3d <HI>Spa.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Were you &s;ucce&s;sful when you adored?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>4th <HI>Spa.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Um!&mdash;Why the chances were again&s;t me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>3d <HI>Spa.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How &s;o?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>4th <HI>Spa.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I adored eleven, and obtained but five, &mdash;'Twas hard, for a man who was &s;o con&s;tant to'em.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t <HI>Spa.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well, we are all Soldiers. War is the mi&s;tre&s;s I per&s;ue.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d <HI>Spa,</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You mu&s;t take pains to keep &s;ight of her, for you have lo&s;t one eye in her &s;ervice al|ready..</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1th <HI>Spa.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Wounds of honour, brother, form the Warrior's proude&s;t Epitaph. My lo&s;s perhaps may live in &s;tory.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>4th <HI>Spa.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>It mu&s;t live in a blind &s;tory, then, if it live at all, brother.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>3d <HI>Spa.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Come, no more of this.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="27" REF="33">
<SPEAKER>1&s;t <HI>Spa.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, let them proceed. They are only in &s;port. My Comrades know that the breath of a few ribald je&s;ters can never wither the laurels a Soldier gains in protecting his Country.&mdash;Look out!&mdash;Here comes Selim!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SELIM.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d <HI>Spa.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well met.&mdash;We have been a full hour at our po&s;t, here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Your pardon. The entanglements of the Wood retarded my progre&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>3d <HI>Spa.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Now, Comrade:&mdash;The time's at hand when we will redre&s;s you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I know your zeal. A Spahi never permits a brother's injuries to remain unrevenged.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>4th <HI>Spa.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>We'll &s;eize upon Blue-Beard, and dry-&s;have him with a two-edged Scymetar.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>If it be expedient to attack the Ca&s;tle, be cautious, friends, in the procedure. My Fatima, el&s;e, may fall in the confu&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d <HI>Spa.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Fear not that.&mdash;We'll crack the walls like a nut-&s;hell, and extract your mi&s;tre&s;s, &s;afe and &s;ound, like the kernel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>4th <HI>Spa.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Our Hor&s;es &s;tand a few paces hence. Let us mount, and away!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>We will, my Comrades!&mdash;We have &s;ome di&s;tance yet to ride, ere we reach the domain of Abomelique. Prepare,&mdash;I'll follow, in&s;tantly.&mdash; Thanks for your aid.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t <HI>Spa.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, we want no thanks. Men are unworthy of &s;uccour in their own time of need,
<PB N="28" REF="34">
who will not be active to relieve the &s;ufferings of their fellows.&mdash;March, Comrades!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt Spahis.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Now, Fortune! Smile upon a Soldier's ho|ne&s;t love, &s;truggling to re&s;cue injured virtue from oppre&s;&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<DIV4 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Selim.</HI></STAGE>
<LG>
<L>Hear me, O Fortune, hear me!</L>
<L>Thy aid, O let me prove!</L>
<L>Now in this &s;truggle cheer me,</L>
<L>And crown the hopes of Love!</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Then Vice no more &s;hall revel;&mdash;</L>
<L>Yes, Tyrant, we &s;hall meet:</L>
<L>A Soldier's Sword &s;hall level</L>
<L>Oppre&s;&s;ion at my feet,<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE II.</HI> An Apartment in Abomelique's Ca&s;tle.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ABOMELIQUE, FATIMA, and SHACABAC.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Fatima; bu&s;ine&s;s of import calls me &mdash;for a few hours I leave you. Soon as the Sun &s;lopes through the azure vault of Heaven, to ki&s;s the mountain's top, and Evening's lengthen'd &s;ha|dows forerun the dew drops of the night, then look for my return. Then &s;hall out marriage be accompli&s;hed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fat.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Alas!&mdash;if ever pity&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="29" REF="35">
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No more of this&mdash;Off with this maiden coyne&s;s:&mdash;And, in my ab&s;ence, be gay and jo|cund. This Ca&s;tle can afford diver&s;ion, Lady. Rove freely through it.&mdash;Here are the keys&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>involuntarily interrupting</HI></STAGE>What <HI>all</HI> the keys?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Peace, Slave! In&s;pect the rich Apar$|ments. The&s;e open every door:&mdash;This Slave, here, &s;hall conduct you&mdash;But, with them, take this cau|tion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A Caution!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom</HI>:</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes: this Key, &s;parkling with diamonds, opens a door within the blue apartment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>&s;ighing</HI></STAGE>Oh!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That Door, and that alone&mdash;is &s;acred-Dare to open it, and the mo&s;t dreadful puni&s;hment that tongue can utter will await you.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Here</HI> SHACABAC <HI>gives</HI> ABOMELIQUE <HI>a look of &s;uppli|cation for</HI> FATIMA, <HI>and is repelled by a ferocious frown from his</HI> MASTER.</STAGE>
<P>It is the &s;ole re&s;traint I ever &s;hall impo&s;e. In all el&s;e you have ample &s;cope.&mdash;Merit my indulgence, and tremble to abu&s;e it.<STAGE><HI>gives the Keys</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I tremble now, to hear your words, and mark your manner.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>a&s;ide</HI></STAGE>So do I, I'm &s;ure!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>If this Key be of &s;uch import, 'twere be&s;t not tru&s;t it to my keeping.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, much the be&s;t.&mdash;Pray take it again! &mdash;Pray do!<STAGE><HI>anxiou&s;ly</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="30" REF="36">
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Be dumb!&mdash;No, Fatima&punc;&mdash;A Wife were unworthy of my love, could I not confide in her di&s;cretion.&mdash;Prove I may tru&s;t in your's implicitly. &mdash;Follow me, Slave, to the Ca&s;tle gate;&mdash;then ha&s;ten back to attend your mi&s;tre&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I&mdash;Pray then don't &s;tir from here till I come, Lady!&mdash;If the poor &s;oul &s;hould get to the Blue Chamber before I return, and&mdash;<STAGE><HI>a&s;ide</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Farewell, Fatima!&mdash;Come on.<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I come&mdash;Oh!&mdash;<STAGE><HI>fir&s;t looks at</HI> FATIMA, <HI>then at his Ma&s;ter, between anxiety for the one and ter|ror of the other:&mdash;Then Exit, after</HI> ABOMELIQUE.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What can this mean?&mdash;His ferocious look, as he pronounced the &s;olemn charge, &s;truck horror through me!&mdash;The countenance, too, of the trem|bling Slave was mark'd with my&s;tery&punc;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> IRENE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So, Si&s;ter!&mdash;The Ba&s;haw is going, I hear, 'till the evening.&mdash;What are tho&s;e keys in your hand?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>They open every door within the walls.&mdash; Abomelique has left them with me, that we may wander through the Ca&s;tle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well, now, that is very kind of him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I have no joy, now, Irene, in ob&s;erving the idle glitter, and luxury of wealth.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Haven't you?&mdash;but I have. We'll have a rare rummage!&mdash;I won't leave a &s;ingle nook, nor corner, unexamined.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="31" REF="37">
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That mu&s;t not be. There is one room we are forbidden to enter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A forbidden Room!&mdash;Dear, now, I had ra|ther &s;ee that room than any other in the Ca&s;tle! Did the Ba&s;haw forbid us?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He did;&mdash;and with an empha&s;is &s;o earne&s;t, a manner &s;o impre&s;&s;ive, that he has taught me a fa|tal con&s;equence would wait on di&s;obedience.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Mercy!&mdash;How I do long to &s;ee that room!</L>
<L>&mdash;Do let me ju&s;t look at the key.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Beware, Irene!<STAGE><HI>&s;hewing her the key.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Dear, there can be no harm in looking at a key.&mdash;What, is this it?&mdash;Well, it is a mon&s;trous fine one, I declare! Dear Fatima! how pretty it would be ju&s;t to take one peep!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Tempt me not to a breach of faith, Irene. When we betray the confidence repo&s;ed in us, to gratify our curio&s;ity, a crime is coupled to a failing, and we employ a vice to feed a weakne&s;s. &mdash;The door within the blue apartment mu&s;t remain untouch'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I have done:&mdash;but we may &s;ee the re&s;t of the rooms, I &s;uppo&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>If that can plea&s;e you, Si&s;ter, I will ac|company you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That's my good, kind Fatima!&mdash;If I could but get her by degrees to this Blue Apartment! <STAGE><HI>A&s;ide.</HI></STAGE> Come;&mdash;we'll go, and look over the Ca&s;tle.&mdash;I &s;aw &s;ome rich dre&s;&s;es, in a wardrobe, at
<PB N="32" REF="38">
the end of the gallery, that would have &s;uited me, nicely, in the dance la&s;t night.</P>
</SP>
<DIV4 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Irene.</HI></STAGE>
<LG>
<L>Moving to the melody of mu&s;ick's note,</L>
<L>Ob&s;erve the Turki&s;h fair advance,</L>
<L>Lightly as the Go&s;&s;amer &s;he &s;eems to float,</L>
<L>Thro' mazes of the Dance.</L>
<L>Sportive is the mea&s;ure,</L>
<L>Thrilling is the plea&s;ure,</L>
<L>While in merry glee, the Sexes join;</L>
<L>Deeper-blu&s;hing ro&s;es,</L>
<L>Ev'ry cheek di&s;clo&s;es,</L>
<L>Eyes with Lu&s;tre &s;hine.</L>
<L>Moving to the melody, &amp;c.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>When the lover takes her glowing hand,</L>
<L>With manly grace and ea&s;e,</L>
<L>Can the dancing female, then, with&s;tand</L>
<L>His gentle &s;queeze?</L>
<L>No&mdash;She gives him then &s;o langui&s;hing a glance,</L>
<L>Grown tender, &s;oft, and melting with the dance.</L>
<L>Cupid, Cupid&mdash;God of hearts,</L>
<L>Dancing &s;harpens all your darts!</L>
<L>Moving to the melody, &amp;c.<STAGE><HI>Exeunt.</HI></STAGE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE III.</HI> Another Apartment in <HI>ABOMELIQUE's</HI> Ca&s;tle.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> IBRAHIM, <HI>running after</HI> BEDA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Come here you little &s;kipping jade, and let
<PB N="33" REF="39">
me look at you!&mdash;<STAGE><HI>takes hold of her.</HI></STAGE> Tell me now, Don't you think you are very pretty?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I am &s;uch as Nature made me, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nature has been very kind to you, hu&s;&s;ey! She has given you two black eyes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That wasn't &s;o very kind of her, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Don't you know I am ma&s;$e <HI>Major Domo?</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes.&mdash;The Ba&s;haw has given you the command, it &s;eems, over the &s;laves.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then obey me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How?&mdash;Why&mdash;Shew me your teeth.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My teeth?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes.&mdash;Giggle.&mdash;<STAGE>BEDA <HI>laughs</HI>.</STAGE> O, Maho|met!&mdash;There's ivory!&mdash;She has a hand&s;omer mouth than an elephant!&mdash;Where were you born, child?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>In Con&s;tantinople, Sir. My poor mother was carried off with a plague, there. My father had it at the &s;ame time.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Did it kill him, then?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No, Sir:&mdash;he was very bad with it:&mdash;but when my mother died&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then your Father got rid of his Plague.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I don't doubt it. And, how came you a &s;lave?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>O, that's a very long &s;tory.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Don't tell it, then. We've no need of long
<PB N="34" REF="40">
&s;tories, while there's opium in Turkey:&mdash;But I'll lighten the load of your bondage,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Will you, indeed, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes.&mdash;I am a true Turki&s;h lover.&mdash;And know all the amorous phra&s;eology of our Country. &mdash;You &s;hall be the Nutmeg of my affections, my All-&s;pice of delight. When I meet you in the grove of Nightingales, let not your eyes be di&s;|dainful as the Stag's.&mdash;There!&mdash;Now, go and tell Mu&s;tapha to mend the hole the rat gnaw'd in my &s;lipper la&s;t night!&mdash;in that damn'd cock-loft my &s;on-in-law crams me into, by way of a bed|chamber.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Am I to go now, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye.&mdash;Stay!&mdash;Give me a ki&s;s fir&s;t.&mdash;What you are loth to take it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>O, Sir, we &s;laves mu&s;t take any thing.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>He ki&s;&s;es her.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Adieu!&mdash;Crown of my head!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Beda.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Good bye, Sir!&mdash;An old dotard!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> BEDA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My fortune's made! Abomelique marries my daughter to-night, and puts me into power, be|cau&s;e he can't help it.</P>
</SP>
<DIV4 TYPE="song">
<PB N="35" REF="41">
<HEAD>SONG.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Ibrahim.</HI></STAGE>
<LG>
<L><HI>Major Domo</HI> am I</L>
<L>Of this grand Family;</L>
<L>My word through the Ca&s;tle prevails:</L>
<L>I'm appointed the Head</L>
<L>That mu&s;t keep up the dread,</L>
<L>And the pomp, of my Son-in-Laws Tail$.</L>
<L>I &s;trut as fine as any Macaw,</L>
<L>I'll change for down my bed of &s;traw,</L>
<L>On perqui&s;ites I lay my paw,</L>
<L>I pour wine, &s;lily, down my maw,</L>
<L>I &s;tuff good victuals in my craw.</L>
<L>'Tis a very fine thing to be Father-in-Law</L>
<L>To a very magnificent three tail'd Ba&s;haw!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2">
<HEAD>II.</HEAD>
<L>The Slaves, black and white,</L>
<L>Of each Sex own my might;</L>
<L>I command full three hundred and ten.</L>
<L>The Females I'll ki&s;s,</L>
<L>But it won't be ami&s;s</L>
<L>To fright them, with thumping the Men&punc;</L>
<L>I &s;trut as fine &amp;c.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3">
<HEAD>III.</HEAD>
<L>At the Head of Affairs,</L>
<L>Turn me out, then who dares.&mdash;</L>
<L>Let them prove the Head pilfers and &s;teals:</L>
<L>No three tail'd Ba&s;haw</L>
<L>Kicks his Father-in-Law,</L>
<L>And makes his Head take to his Heels.</L>
<L>I &s;trut as fine &amp;c.<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> IBRAHIM.</STAGE></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="36" REF="42">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE IV.</HI> The Blue Apartment.</HEAD>
<STAGE>FATIMA <HI>and</HI> IRENE <HI>are di&s;covered on the Top of the Stair-ca&s;e</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I am tired, already, with the &s;earch we have made, Irene.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>O, I could never be tired with &s;uch fine things as we have &s;een!&mdash;Do, now, ju&s;t come down the &s;tair, and walk through this wing of the build|ing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, now, that's a &s;weet, good-natured &s;i&s;ter!&mdash;<STAGE><HI>they de&s;cend the &s;tair.</HI></STAGE>&mdash;Now here's a pretty room!&mdash;All furni&s;h'd with Blue, I &s;ee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>With Blue!&mdash;'tis the very chamber we were caution'd to avoid. Imprudent girl!&mdash;Whi|ther have you led me? Ha&s;te, ha&s;te, Irene, and let us leave it in&s;tantly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Dear! where's the hurry?&mdash;I'm &s;ure 'tis a very pretty room:&mdash;Be&s;ides, 'tis only the <HI>door</HI> in this room, which leads to another, you know, that you were bid not to touch.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No matter: 'Tis ra&s;h to tarry. Our being here may excite &s;u&s;picion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Su&s;picion!&mdash;Why, we have no bad purpo&s;e: &mdash;And, even, if we were to open the door&mdash;and there it &s;tands, as if it &s;eemed to invite the very
<PB N="37" REF="43">
key in your hand to come and unlock it&mdash;Why I &s;ee no &s;uch great crime in the action.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The Ba&s;haw's charge, Irene&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Is a very ill-natured one. And &s;hould you di&s;obey him, we could keep our own coun&s;el.&mdash; Then if nobody knows we have found out his &s;e|cret, what have we to fear, while we continue mute as death?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>A Voice within.</HI> Death!&mdash;(<HI>the women look at each other, and tremble</HI>.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Did you hear nothing, Irene?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes.&mdash;I&mdash;I&mdash;I thought I heard &s;omething that&mdash;Stay&mdash;O, it mu&s;t be an echo.&mdash;The&s;e large old buildings are full of them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>It had an aweful &s;ound!&mdash;A tone like that, they &s;ay, will &s;ail upon the flagged wing of mid|night, cro&s;&s;ing the fear &s;truck traveller upon the de&s;art, to give him token of a foul murder.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>A deep groan is heard from the interior apartment.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>O, Heaven have mercy!&mdash;What can this mean?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I know not!&mdash;It &s;eems the accent of di&s;|tre&s;s.&mdash;If &s;o, it were humanity to &s;uccour the wretched &s;oul who breathes it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Humanity alone, my &s;i&s;ter, could induce me to penetrate the my&s;tery this Portal, here, in|clo&s;es.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No eye can &s;ee us!</P>
</SP>
<Q><PB N="38" REF="44">
<TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1>
<HEAD>DUET.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Fatima</HI> and <HI>Irene</HI>.</STAGE>
<LG>
<L>All is hu&s;h'd! No foot&s;tep falls!</L>
<L>And Silence reigns within the Walls!</L>
<L>The Place invites; the Door is near;</L>
<L>The Time is apt&mdash;The Key is here.</L>
<L>Say &s;hall we! Yes. Say &s;hall we? No!</L>
<L>What is it makes us tremble &s;o!</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Mi&s;chief is not our intent;</L>
<L>Then wherefore fear we &s;hould repent?</L>
<L>Say &s;hall we? Yes. The Door is near.</L>
<L>Say &s;hall we? Yes. The Key is here.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE><HI>At the end of the Duet</HI>, FATIMA <HI>puts the Key in the Door, which &s;inks, and di&s;covers the interior Apart|ment, as at fir&s;t repre&s;ented&mdash;The in&s;cription over the Skeleton's head, is, now</HI>,
<Q>"THE PUNISHMENT OF CURIOSITY."</Q>
<HI>The Blue Chamber undergoes the &s;ame change, as in the fir&s;t in&s;tance. The</HI> WOMEN <HI>&s;hriek, and run to each other, and hide their heads in each others bo|&s;oms.&mdash;At this moment</HI> SHACABAC <HI>appears at the top of the Stair-ca&s;e&mdash;then runs down ha&s;tily. As he de&s;cends, the Door ri&s;es, and the Chamber re&s;umes it's original appearance</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>Speaking as de&s;cending</HI></STAGE>O, 'tis as I fear'd! This comes of her not waiting for me.&mdash;She knows the &s;ecret, and &s;he dies!&mdash;O, Lady! what have you done?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Begone!&mdash;You knew of this. Your look,
<PB N="39" REF="45">
when late Abomelique left me, now is explained.&mdash; You are an accomplice in this bloody bu&s;ine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My Death, no doubt, is certain;&mdash;and, in you, perhaps, I &s;ee my executioner.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How a man's looks may belye him! This comes now, of my being &s;uch an ugly dog!&mdash; I wouldn't hurt a hair of your head to be made a Sultan.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Prove it, then, by &s;aving us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Irene.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Conduct us from the Ca&s;tle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Impo&s;&s;ible. The outward Gates are clo&s;ely guarded.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, nay, you do not pity us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not pity you! &mdash;Oh! he mu&s;t have a hard heart to &s;ee a lovely woman in extremity and not try to &s;often her di&s;tre&s;s.&mdash;Stay!&mdash;Perhaps we may conceal the&mdash;Where's the Key?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>It fell upon the ground and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The ground!&mdash;Aye&mdash;Here&mdash;Perhaps we may be able to&mdash;<STAGE>taking it up</STAGE> Nay, then, every hope is lo&s;t!&mdash;The Key is broke!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>All is di&s;cover'd then!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Certain. O, Fatima! would the Ba&s;haw had any humanity within his brea&s;t, and that fatal Key could unlock it!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>O, would he had! I'd &s;tuff the Key down his throat, as &s;oon as he came home, to get at it&mdash;
<STAGE><PB N="40" REF="46"><HI>The Horn of the Ca&s;tle Gate is &s;ounded.</HI></STAGE>
There!&mdash;The Ba&s;haw return'd!&mdash;full &s;ix hours be|fore his time!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>O Heaven! what are we to do?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I am wreckle&s;s of the future. Perhaps 'twere better I &s;hould die!&mdash;'Twill end a Life, which promi&s;ed nought but mi&s;ery.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Die!&mdash;Oh, Si&s;ter!<STAGE><HI>embracing her.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Do not weep! do not weep!&mdash;I'm almo&s;t di&s;tracted&mdash;Hurry hence&mdash;come, Lady!&mdash;meet him as if nothing had happen'd&mdash;Collect your &s;pirits,&mdash; Smooth your looks.&mdash;This way, now!&mdash;O! if choak|ing can &s;ave your Life, my &s;orrow for you bids fair to pre&s;erve it. Come, Lady, come!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt, up Stair ca&s;e.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="5" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE V.</HI> Another Apartment in the Ca&s;tle.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SHACABAC.&mdash;<HI>looking behind him as he enters</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I have left them on the top of the Stair, that I may avoid ob&s;ervation.&mdash;If they get far enough from the Blue Chamber before inquiry is made for them, they may conceal the&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> HASSAN. (<HI>Shacabac runs again&s;t him</HI>.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Umph!&mdash;Who's that?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ha&s;.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ha&s;&s;an&mdash;The black Eunuch.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Whither are you going?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="41" REF="47">
<SPEAKER><HI>Ha&s;.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To &s;eek the Lady Fatima by the Ba&s;haw's order.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Are you?&mdash;If he meets them &s;o near the fatal Chamber, and mentions it to the Ba&s;haw, they are lo&s;t.&mdash;I mu&s;t detain him.&mdash;I&mdash;Ha&s;&s;an!&mdash; I &s;ay, Ha&s;&s;an&mdash;How d'ye do, Ha&s;&s;an?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ha&s;.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I'm well, I thank you, Shacabac.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well, are you?&mdash;Are you &s;ure you are well?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ha&s;.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Very well.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Very well?&mdash;Very well, I'm glad of it.&mdash; So am I, thank you, Ha&s;&s;an. That is I'm tolerable as the time goes.&mdash;But you had never the kindne&s;s to a&s;k <HI>me</HI>;&mdash;Me, you fellow Slave!&mdash;Pray, now, do a&s;k me:&mdash;Do,&mdash;for that will take up a little time.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>A&s;ide.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ha&s;.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why then, how dy'e do Shacabac?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Very ill indeed, Ha&s;&s;an!&mdash;Only feel my pul&s;e.&mdash;Count it 'till it beats ju&s;t one hundred and twenty.&mdash;Twice &s;ixty &s;econds will delay him about two minutes.<STAGE><HI>a&s;ide.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ha&s;.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I don't know how to count Shacabac.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Don't you?&mdash;Why not?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ha&s;.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I can't read.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That's a good rea&s;on.&mdash;I &s;hould think, ere this, they are far enough from the Blue Chamber to&mdash;A little longer to make all &s;ure. <STAGE><HI>a&s;ide</HI></STAGE> I have been thinking Ha&s;&s;an, why you and I &s;hould be of different colours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="42" REF="48">
<SPEAKER><HI>Ha&s;.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Fortune has di&s;po&s;ed it &s;o&mdash;She has made me black, and you white;&mdash;but don't let that motify you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>It &s;han't. But as you &s;ay, Ha&s;&s;an, Fortune will make men of different &s;hades.&mdash;Fortune's chec|quer'd;&mdash;and &s;he checquers men alternately&mdash;black and white&mdash;like the Squares in the Ba&s;haw's Che&s;s-B$ard.&mdash;When I think how much Fortune is chec|quer'd, I think&mdash;I think that&mdash;I think I have almo&s;t kept you long enough for my purpo&s;e <STAGE><HI>a&s;ide</HI></STAGE> What are the Ba&s;haw's orders to the Lady Fatima?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ha&s;.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That he mu&s;t attend her, in&s;tantly, in the Garden.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>In the Garden?&mdash;Was that the command, Ha&s;&s;an?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ha&s;.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>It was, Shacabac.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then I'll tell you what, Ha&s;&s;an&mdash;if ever the Ma&s;ter of the Slaves gave you a &s;ound drubbing, for &s;taying &s;o long on a me&s;&s;age, you'll get one now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ha&s;.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why have you delay'd me, then?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I!&mdash;You have delay'd me. You have a brain for bu&s;ine&s;s, Ha&s;&s;an;&mdash;but, whenever you meet any one in your way, you will &s;top, and gab|ble.&mdash;That's your fault&mdash;Away!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ha&s;.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I'll go find her.<STAGE><HI>Exit Ha&s;&s;an</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sha.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And I'll to the Garden, to watch her inter|view with the Ba&s;haw: And weak as my means are, I'll catch at every &s;traw to pre&s;erve her!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit Shacabac.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="6" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="43" REF="49">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE VI.</HI> A Garden.&mdash;In the back of which is a part of Abomelique's Ca&s;tle&mdash;and a Draw-bridge leading to the Ca&s;tle Gate. &mdash;A Corridor before the Apartments on the fir&s;t &s;tory. &mdash;A Door beneath it. &mdash; A Turret on the top of the Building overlooking the Countey.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ABOMELIQUE, <HI>and a</HI> SLAVE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Is Fatima inform'd I wait her pre&s;ence here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Slave.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ha&s;&s;an by your command&mdash;She comes.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> FATIMA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Leave us.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit Slave</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>in apparent confu&s;ion</HI></STAGE>This &s;peedy return I&mdash; I look'd not for.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I had accounts to &s;ettle,&mdash;with Traders,&mdash; Merchants from Gallipoli: But when worldly bu&s;i|ne&s;s draws men abroad who leave their hearts at home, then, Fatima, Love's wings give &s;wiftne&s;s to the leaden hours of dull negotiation; and the mercu|rial &s;pirit of an enamour'd mind con&s;olidates a vo|lume, ere Commerce, dozing o'er his Day-book, can plod a page. How have your hours pa&s;&s;'d in my ab&s;ence? Have you view'd the Ca&s;tle?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I have, &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="44" REF="50">
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well, &s;aw you aught worthy your in&s;pec|tion?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Worthy, &s;ir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye worthy&mdash;There are &s;ights here, per|haps, that common eyes ne'er look'd upon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There are indeed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Now, plea&s;e you, give me back the Keys.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>They are here,<STAGE><HI>delivers them in great agita|tion.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How now?&mdash;You tremble!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Tremble, Sir!&mdash;Why &s;hould I?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You be&s;t can an&s;wer that.&mdash;Sometimes, Lady, 'twill betray Guilt.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And know You, then, no in&s;tance where the Guilty do <HI>not</HI> betray them&s;elves by trembling?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Umph!&mdash;I comprehend not that. One Key is wanting! where is it?<STAGE><HI>&s;trenly.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I have it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Give it me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Be not impatient.&mdash;'Tis in my pocket.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Produce it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall&mdash;but, by mere accident, you &s;ee 'tis broken.<STAGE><HI>gives it.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Damnation!&mdash;Lady, this Key is Charm-fraught; forged in a &s;ulphurous Cave, within who&s;e blood-be&s;prinkled mouth nothing but Witchcraft enters, to celebrate her frantick revels. This &s;peaks a damning proof again&s;t you, and you die!<STAGE><HI>draws
<PB N="45" REF="51">
his Scymetar and holds it over her head.&mdash;She falls on her Knees.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Spare me! Spare me!&mdash;If ever I ap|proach'd the door but to&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No prote&s;tations!<STAGE><HI>going to &s;trike.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Be&s;eech you, hold!&mdash;Alas! if I mu&s;t die, grant me &s;ome little time, for preparation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>After a &s;hort pau&s;e</HI></STAGE>&mdash;Well,&mdash;be it &s;o. Yonder's your chamber. <STAGE><HI>pointing to an Apartment within the Corridor.</HI></STAGE> Thither in&s;tantly: &s;oon expect me there&mdash;then to expiate your crime by Death.&mdash; Before me to the Ca&s;tle!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> FATIMA <HI>through the Door under the Corridor</HI>, ABOMELIQUE <HI>following her with his drawn Scy|metar</HI>.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SHACABAC, <HI>on the oppo&s;ite &s;ide</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Allah, pre&s;erve her poor &s;oul! But I fear &s;he goes to certain Death! O that I were able to &s;ave her! Are there no means to&mdash;This helli&s;h Abomelique whips off women's heads as if they were a parcel of buttons.&mdash;Let me li&s;ten.</P>
<STAGE>FATIMA <HI>comes from her Apartment, upon the Cor|ridor</HI>.</STAGE>
<P>Hi&s;t! Lady! Lady Fatima!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>O get you hence, good fellow! Your anxie|ty may make you a &s;harer with me, in the Ba&s;haw's re&s;entment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Where is he?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="46" REF="52">
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I expect him in&s;tantly to a&s;cend the Stair, and execute his dreadful purpo&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>O, Mahomet, holy Prophet! if ever you break a Ba&s;haw's neck over a Stair-ca&s;e, now's your time!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hark!&mdash;I hear him!&mdash;No.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>IRENE <HI>appears on the Top of the Turret</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Si&s;ter! Si&s;ter Fatima!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Irene! Is it you?&mdash;O, Si&s;ter, fare you well! I die a cruel death!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My heart bleeds for you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So does mine, I'm &s;ure!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Should Travellers appear, I'll call to them to &s;uccour us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>Calling from</HI> FATIMA<HI>'s Apartment</HI>,</STAGE>Fati|ma!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>O, Heaven! he has enter'd the Apartment!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>Without</HI></STAGE>Why Fatima!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis he!<STAGE><HI>retires under the Corridor.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>One moment, I be&s;eech you! I have but one poor prayer to offer up to Heaven, and then I come.&mdash;Is there no help!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="47" REF="53">QUARTETTO.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Abomelique, Fatima, Irene, Shacabac.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Look from the Turret, &s;i&s;ter dear!</L>
<L>And &s;ee if &s;uccour be not near.&mdash;</L>
<L>O tell me what do you de&s;cry?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing but dreary Land and Sky.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati:</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Alas! Alas! then I, mu&s;t die!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire:</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Alas! Alas! then You, mu&s;t die!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac:</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Alas! Alas! then She, mu&s;t die!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Prepare.&mdash;<HI>Fati.</HI>&mdash;He calls! Look out, again!</L>
<L>Look out, look out acro&s;s the plain!</L>
<L>Ah me! does nothing meet your eyes?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ee a Cloud of Du&s;t ari&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That Cloud of Du&s;t a hope &s;upplies!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That Cloud of Du&s;t a hope &s;upplies!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That Cloud of Du&s;t a hope &s;upplies!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No more delay.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A moment &s;tay!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>O, watch the Travellers, my Si&s;ter dear!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I'll wave my handkerchief, 'twill draw them near.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>They'll &s;ee it &s;peedily, and hurry here,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Abom.</SPEAKER>
<P>Prepare!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ee them galloping, they're &s;purring on amain!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Now, fa&s;ter galloping, they &s;kim along the plain!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No more delay.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A moment &s;tay!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>They come.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>They come.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>They come.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Prepare!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>They'll be too late!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>They'll be too late!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>They'll be too late!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Now they di&s;mount!&mdash;They're at the Gate!&mdash;</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Prepare!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="48" REF="54">ABOMELIQUE, <HI>as they fini&s;h the</HI> Quartetto, <HI>ru&s;hes from the Apartment upon the Corridor, &s;eizes</HI> FATI|MA, <HI>and is upon the point of beheading her, when</HI> SELIM <HI>and his Companions having cro&s;&s;'d the Draw|bridge, &s;ound the Horn loudly at the Gate</HI>.&mdash;ABOME|LIQUE, <HI>alarm'd at the Noi&s;e, retires ha&s;tily, dragging</HI> FATIMA <HI>into the Apartment</HI>.</STAGE>
<STAGE>SHACABAC <HI>comes from under the Corridor</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE><HI>to Selim, who is on the Drawbridge,</HI></STAGE>You'll get no entrance there.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Say, where is Fatima!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Trembling under the Ba&s;haw's clutches.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>We force the Gate, then.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis impo&s;&s;ible. Get round to the Ea&s;tern Battlement; we are weake&s;t there.&mdash;Away! and &s;uc|ce&s;s attend you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To judge you from your conduct, you &s;hould be a friend. What are you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What every man &s;hould be&mdash;a Friend to Virtue in di&s;tre&s;s wherever I meet it. Away, or you will be too late.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Come, Comrades!&mdash;be firm! fight lu&s;tily. Quick March!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>They hurry from the Bridge, to quick Martial Mu&s;ick.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Exit Shacabac.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="7" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="49" REF="55">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE VII.</HI> An Apartment in the Ca&s;tle.</HEAD>
<STAGE>ALARUMS, SHOUTS, &amp;c.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> A BODY OF SLAVES.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t <HI>Slave.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>We are attack'd.&mdash;Up to the Ram|parts.&mdash;Where is Ibrahim, our Leader?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d <HI>Slave.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He's no where to be found.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t <HI>Slave.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>We mu&s;t begin without him, then. It is the Ba&s;haw's order.&mdash;Follow!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt Slaves.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Shouts without.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> IBRAHIM.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mercy on me!&mdash;I quake in my cloaths like a cold jelly in a bag! They are battering the Ca&s;tle to pieces. I am the unluckie&s;t Mu&s;&s;ulman in all Turkey! Here's a Building that has &s;tood wind and weather this age, and, the moment I pop my no&s;e into it, it begins tumbling about my ears.&mdash;</P>
<STAGE><HI>Shouts.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>A cry of</HI> TO ARMS! TO ARMS!</STAGE>
<P>To Arms! O, dear!&mdash;I had much rather to Legs, if I knew which way to e&s;cape. Now &s;hall I be ex|pected to put my&s;elf in the front of the ranks, be|cau&s;e I am <HI>Major-Domo</HI>;&mdash;but, if I do, I'll give them leave to mince the <HI>Major-Domo</HI> for his Son-in-Law's &s;upper.<STAGE>ALARUM.</STAGE></P>
<STAGE><PB N="50" REF="56"><HI>Enter</HI> 1&s;t. SLAVE.</STAGE>
<P>O Mahomet! what's that?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t. <HI>Slave.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>An Enemy is on the Walls.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then, you cowardly ra&s;cal, do you go and knock him into the ditch.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t. <HI>Slave.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>We wait for you. You are appointed our Leader&mdash;There is no di&s;cipline without you.&mdash; We want a Head.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Do you?&mdash;So &s;hall I, if I go with you.&mdash; Get on before&mdash;Tell 'em to fight like fury;&mdash;and I'll be with them, to reward their valour, when it's all over.&mdash;Run that way, that leads into the action.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t. <HI>Slave.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I will.<STAGE><HI>Exit Slave.</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ibra.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And I'll run this way, that leads out of it.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Shouts Alarum, &amp;c.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE LAST.</HI> The in&s;ide of the Sepulchre.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>The In&s;cription, over the Skeleton's head, is now</HI>,&mdash; THIS SEPULCHRE SHALL INCLOSE HER WHO MAY $$DANGER THE LIFE OF ABOMELI|$$$&mdash;</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>He $houts and Alarums continue.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Ent$$</HI> ABOMELIQUE <HI>with his Scymetar drawn&mdash;drag|gi$$ in</HI> FATIMA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>On every &s;ide it rages: The Slaves give way. You &s;till are in my power. You Sorcere&s;s,
<PB N="51" REF="57">
have led me to the toil! Your Death will extricate me&mdash;Meet it then here:&mdash;Here, in the Sepulchr$, which you have violated.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay take me hence.&mdash;Let me not peri&s;h in this abode of horror!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Thy prayers are vain.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>As he rai&s;es his Scymetar to &s;trike, a near Attack is heard, and a violent cra&s;h in the Building:&mdash;Part of the wall, in the back of the Sepulchre, towards the roof, is beat down, and</HI> SELIM <HI>appears in the Aperture</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hold, Ruffian! hold they arm!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh Selim!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ra&s;h fool! I know thee, and thy purpo&s;e. Thy pre&s;ence, now, &s;wells the full tide of my re&s;ent|ment, and gives a higher ze&s;t to vengeance. Know the decrees of De&s;tiny, and cur&s;e thy weakne&s;s which would counteract it.&mdash;"This Sepulchre &s;hall inclo&s;e Her who &s;hall endanger the Life of Abomeli|que." This wretch, here, has endanger'd it&mdash;This Sepulchre inclo&s;es her, and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But not in Death; Tyrant, thy hell-born Spells promi&s;e not that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Does my Fate juggle with me, then!&mdash; Hold&mdash;No yon dagger is my &s;afe-guard <STAGE><HI>pointing to the Tali&s;man</HI></STAGE> 'till mortal hands can reach it. Weak boy! De&s;pair, and &s;ee her die.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>While Selim lives&mdash;So near me too,&mdash;my life is precious, and I &s;truggle to pre&s;erve it.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="52" REF="58"><HI>She &s;truggles with</HI> ABOMELIQUE, <HI>who attempts to kill her;&mdash;and, in the &s;truggle, &s;natches the Dagger from the pede&s;tal of the Skeleton.&mdash;The Skeleton ri&s;es on his feet&mdash;lifts his arm which holds the Dart, and keeps it &s;u&s;pended. At that in&s;tant the entire wall of the Se|pulchre falls to pieces, and admits</HI> SELIM <HI>to the ground.&mdash;Behind&mdash;among fragments of the building, a body of</HI> SPAHIS <HI>is di&s;covered, on foot, with</HI> ABOME|LIQUE's SLAVES <HI>under their Sabres, in po&s;tures of &s;ub|mi&s;&s;ion, and farther back is &s;een a large Troop of Hor&s;e&mdash;The neighbouring Country terminates the view</HI>.</STAGE>
<STAGE>SLIM <HI>advances towards</HI> ABOMELIQUE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Now, turn thee hither!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Abom.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Baffled!&mdash;I &s;till have mortal means, and thus I u&s;e them.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>SELIM <HI>and</HI> ABOMELIQUE <HI>fight with Scymetars&mdash;During the Combat, Enter</HI> IRENE <HI>and</HI> SHACABAC.&mdash;<HI>After a hard conte&s;t</HI>, SELIM <HI>overthrows</HI> ABOMELIQUE <HI>at the foot of the Skeleton.&mdash;The Skeleton in&s;tantly plunges the Dart, which he has held &s;u&s;pended, into the brea&s;t of</HI> ABOMELIQUE, <HI>and &s;inks with him beneath the earth. (A volume of Flame ari&s;es, and the earth clo&s;es.)</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE>SELIM <HI>and</HI> FATIMA <HI>embrace</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Huzza!&mdash;If ever the Ba&s;haw was in fit $ompa$$&punc; $word$ got into it now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>F$t.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>$span$</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="53" REF="59">
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Thus &s;afe, at la&s;t, I cla&s;p thee!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ire.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Joy, joy, my Si&s;ter! we have conquer'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Fati.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Where is my Father?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Shac.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hid in the du&s;t-hole.&mdash;when the noi&s;e is over, we may chance to get &s;ight of him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>All &s;hall be explain'd: Our Marriage now, my Fatima, may meet his &s;anction&mdash;And you my hone&s;t fellow mu&s;t not go unrewarded <STAGE><HI>to Shacabac.</HI></STAGE> &mdash;Thanks my brave Comrades!&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>SPAHIS <HI>and</HI> SLAVES <HI>come forward</HI>.</STAGE>
<P>We are victors&mdash;and in the countenance, here, of every Slave I &s;ee a &s;mile impre&s;t, which betokens joy, in having lo&s;t a Tyrant.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Slaves.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Thanks to our Deliverer!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Come, Fatima.&mdash;Let us away from this rude S$ene of horror:&mdash;and ble&s;s the Providence which nerves the arm of Virtue to humble Vice, and Op|pre&s;&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<DIV4 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>CHORUS.</HEAD>
<L>Mon&s;ters of Hell, and Noxious Night,</L>
<L>How! your Songs of wild delight!</L>
<L>To your gloomy Caves de&s;cending,</L>
<L>His $treer of Murder ending,</L>
<L>No$ the Tyrant's Spirit flies:</L>
<L>Bathed in a flood</L>
<L>Of guilty Blood,</L>
<L>He dies! He dies!</L>
<L><PB N="54" REF="60">How great is the tran&s;port, the joy how complete,</L>
<L>When, rai&s;ed from De&s;pair, thus Love's votaries meet!</L>
<L>Sweet the Delight that Lovers prove!</L>
<L>Sweet, when Fortune, tired of frowning,</L>
<L>Hymen comes, with plea&s;ure crowning</L>
<L>Happy Love!</L>
</DIV4>
</DIV3>
